In Sevens, the team which first scores points throughout the game wins. To start a game, a coin is tossed between the captains; the captain treats the round as a free kick if the coin lands heads-up, and as penalty point if it hits tails. The first team to score two extra points wins. A point may be scored through a try or a goal. The same player must score them, except that in war-time, another player may be on point if first cannot score. Points can also be scored if two or more players tackle the ball carrier. Teams can score by touch using the foot or by kicking the ball, although kicking the ball while its in touch with the ground is not allowed.
a: This game progresses with like-numbered teams having a turn to kick a soccer ball into a goal. The side which kicks the ball into the goal advances by kicking up a rugby-style ball in the air and getting that ball behind the opposing team's goalposts, without having the ball touch the ground inside of the opponents' end lines. This continues until one team scores the goal; the team gets the ball into play again for the next goal. There is a popular variation of this where players squeeze the ball before kicking it to gasp it in the goal.

The competition lasts exactly seven days with the first step on Sunday starting at 10 am and concluding at 10 pm, and the last step starting at 10 am and ending at 10 pm. Each team plays every other team, and each has a three-day rest after their first seven in each tier.
- Seven-plus game: A Sevens game which adds an additional boost of stamina and speed to the sport is described as a "Seven's plus". In essence, the game is played to the same scoring criteria. However, the points for kicking the ball into a goal immediately are retained, except for goals scored directly from free kicks after a score. In addition to the above, the team with touch in the play score an ten-point bonus, which is proportionate to the size of the opposing team. The first team to reach a score of either 40 or 100 is the winner. The International Rugby Board (the world governing body for the sport) has recently issued guidelines for the scoring system and the "points" gained/forfeited in the additional scenario.

query: The cinnamon quail-thrush (Cinclosoma cinnamomeum) is a species of bird in the family Cinclosomatidae. Endemic to Australia, it
completion:
was described by Richard Lydekker in 1889. Its common name commemorates the early international prominence of cinnamon quail-thrush specimen concerts.
Its anatomical features are well known and have stimulated scientific interest.
The cinnamon quail-thrush has a brown back and the hindneck is rich cinnamon. Both sexes are alike but the male-bird has a richer colour. The contour feathers on the back, rump and lower back are minimally mottled with obvious streaks. The basal half of the tail feathers are being whiter than the uppertail coverts. The throat is whitish, mottled with darker shades, and the wings and back are distinctive streaked. The chest is pale cinnamon. The pectoral, underwing and upperwing coverts have a coppery iridescence. The rest of the face is cinnamon but with some reddish patches around the nostrils. There is a prominent mid-line stripe above the eye, extending to the auriculars. The forehead is cinnamon and there are also some cinnamon streaks on the cheeks, below the eye (noting that the sexes are similar as the male and female’s coloration)
The petal of the female quail-thrush has a rich red-brown color, narrower than the males petal.
The young female quail-thrush exhibits the feature factor of cinnamon rather than red, and has a richer brown contrast body color.

query: Carcharodontosauridae (carcharodontosaurids; from the Greek carcharodontosauros: "shark-toothed lizards") is
completion:
a clade or informal grouping of theropods containing carcharodontosaurids and their close relatives, including their ancestors Sinraptor and Megalosaurus.
Recent discoveries of the giant predators Giganotosaurus, Carcharodontosaurus and Neovenator have strengthened supporting evidence for a basal position of carcharodontosaurids within Herrerasauria. However, several recent phylogenetic trees, including the influential study by Hutchinson et al. 1970, place carcharodontosaurids as the sister group to Tetanurae, and hence more basal. Although neural arch and pelvis morphology is unknown in many carcharodontosaurid fossils, it is speculated that basal theropods and carcharodontosaurids may have been rather similar to each other.
This article includes a list of references, but its sources remain unclear because it has insufficient inline citations. (March 2013) (Learn how and when to remove this template message)
Carcharodontosauridae comprises the genera Megalosaurus, Carcharodontosaurus, Giganotosaurus and possibly Carcharodontops. A cladistic analysis including suggested synapomorphies found several notable morphology differences between carcharodontosaurids (characteristic of the most recent/basal carcharodontosaurids) and carcharodontosaurines. However, this study did not include well-known basal carcharodontosaurines Giganotosaurus and Carcharodontops, which is perhaps due to the poor resolution of the phylogeny (a pair of basal carcharodontosaurines is missing). Several other small-bodied theropods, such as the abelisaur Segisaurus were also suggested to be closely related to the basal carcharodontosaurids but were in fact only close relatives. Other characters shared with carcharodontosaurids as observed by the cladistic analysis include: subrostrally broad skull roof, great prominence of the tooth serrations and transverse ridge on the surangular bone, orbital circumference no more than ca. 1.5 times skull depth, elongated maxilla about 3 times skull length, paraphyses on the malleus with stout medial processes, and serrate lateral surface of the scapula..
The main advantage of the most recent phylogenetic tree predicting the basal status of carcharodontosaurids, is that it provides a hypothesis for the function of the longer, robust hindlimbs in relation to the short, lightly built hindlimbs in Megalosaurus (2.8 m) as hypothesized by Phelps 1967. Without neurological information of the forelimb, it has been suspected that the more robust hindlimbs were primarily for aquatic activities. The hypothesis of greater hindlimb size was widely proposed as support for a swim-powered lifestyle in carcharodontosaurids, however the evolutionary basis of this hypothesis remains controversial.
In a study performed of the distribution of swimlevel "swimming connectives" in 66 theropod taxa, the swimlevel "swimming connectives" (required to propel the forelimbs under water) were found to be absent in carcharodontosaurids indicating that their swimming style was likely not involved in their terrestrial lifestyle. These findings suggest that the biomechanics of swimming was for carcharodontosaurids little different from baryonychines. Due to the paucity of fossil data, it is also unclear whether or not swimming abilities were used by contemporary carcharodontosaurids during hunting.
Per scratch marks on reputedly sauropods in the Lourinha Formation in Portugal, it has been hypothesized that carcharodontosaurids were responsible for predating half of sauropods in the formation. The recovered comminuted bone, which confirms scratch marks, was found in Carcharodontosaurus saharicus and Dakosaurus from the Kannur District of Kerala State in India, as well as in Carcharodontosaurus wakefieldi, conclusion that were analyzed in the same study. Predatory gait was either unable of carcharodontosaurids (due to non-transverse lumbar vertebrae) in these "predelphodonts". However, studies of hip anatomy of carcharodontosaurids such as Carcharodontosaurus, and assumptions that they retained primitive sauropodomorph hips and similar limb proportions, echo cursorial hypotheses that they could gallop or engage in slow running. According to the study, however, it is also plausible that the data analyzed represented traumatized material. A study reporting reputed saw marks on an ungual phalanx caused during an predation event, suggests similar methodology.

query: Peregian Beach within the Sunshine Coast Region comprises continual residential development along the eastern coastal strip of sandy beaches. The David Low Way passes north to south through this area. Development to the west is constrained by
completion:
the Whitsunday and Stanley River floodplains. A large deepwater channel (Campey Channel or Mitchell Sound) separates the northern half of the area from Cairns and the southern half from the Accommodation Coastlands Region, and is generally less than 10m deep. Surges from major storms may raise the floor of the channel enough to bridge the separation between different parts of the area. Originally, much of this area was covered by wet forests dominated by mangrove trees, tidal flats and swamps. Today, the area is predominantly industrial (particularly sugar cane) and urban.

A subsurface water barrier is seen in the barrier ridges along the Cairns Range, particularly in relatively deep weathering profiles where there is a regional anticlinal structure in the underlying Gabbalong Group (Miocene sediments). This local structure fragments the groundwater flow system for the upper Providence area. Groundwater flow is commonly east to west from the surrounding coastal catchments.
· Westaway Formation: The layer of hardpan within this formation extends through a considerable area east of the Cairns Range, but it is more prominent between the Cairns Range and the Whitsunday Island Coastal Area. Beneath the top of this formation there is typically loose gravel, clay and silt. Towards the east and south there are also sandstone and siltstone lenses within the vegetated complex.
· Aukland limestone: This is exposed in a series of patches between the Whitsunday Island Coastal Area and the Cairns Range. Subsequent erosion cut these into a pattern of interfingers with Watepurupah Formation units nearby. The most obvious is a thrust with north-south N45°E strike cutting into riftway limestone beside its sedimentary cover.
· Watepurupah Formation (Miocene): The major water yield comes from alluvial aquifers in physiographic depressions extending from offshore North to South Sea Islands, through Bowen Gap and north to George Point, Whitsunday Island. The major aquifer in this area is the Ribbon Reef-Green Cliff Formation (opened by geothermal faults). The unconformity (thread) between formations is commonly 60 – 120m deep, suggesting ground swells of restricted importance are relatively short-lived. Wells penetrating into these indurated formations have intermittent flow. The Arcadia Formation with its complex dispositional pattern usually breaks up the aquifer to produce separate flow units at different locations. Haippys and Mangamesse formations are common near the Whitsunday Island Coastal Area. Bores, with few exceptions, penetrate the aeolianites and Watenme Yammeruab Formation west of the Cairns Range.
· Shiplipka Formation (periglacial gravel and sand andesite): Groundwater flow is vadose and preferential and haslevated erosional resistance with flanking ridges and transition outcrops.
· MacPherson Thena Formation (mainly flat sand bathtub: water conjunctive transects of worse-case groundwater supply performance.
The most substantial management issue for the area is the extraction of land for development and urbanization. The cumulative impact of future development on groundwater depends on the degree of recharge by streams and other sources as less rain can result in lower aquifer levels and a reduction in freshwater discharge to the coast. The State Priority Plan (SPP) 2014: State Water Supply Strategy 2014 - 2023 notes that the cumulative effects of continued urban expansion could lead to water shortages in 50 years if approaches are not significantly different to current conditions. This may include an overall decline in reservoir storage of more than 10% by 2050. Climate scenarios and modelling provide better insight into water availability for the Sunshine Coast area. Rainfall averages for the 300km eastern half of the region indicate a rainfall reduction in excess of 100mm per year for each 1°C rise. Some scenarios indicate a 10% coverage total as result of 11mm/m rise in temperature. 20-30% coverage is noted in the Honiara-Heron Park area and 10-20% in the Jacob River area. Water that falls in the coastal marine areas is accounted for when used for supply purposes. These areas are typically connected to groundwater. Raising water in these areas has the potential to drain Cairns catchments. As might be expected, the Sunshine coast is more vinated (ie has greater rainfall) than the Whitsundays.

query: The cinnamon quail-thrush (Cinclosoma cinnamomeum) is a species of bird in the family Cinclosomatidae. Endemic to Australia, it
completion:
has been caught at a few resorts. It is considered extinct in the wild and survives only in captivity.
Being incapable to fly for long distances, and unable to cross waterholes to look for food, Cinnamon Quail-thrushes are confined to a small area in which they are obligatorily perched, and dependent on foraging insects.
Although a detailed study of Cinnamon Quail-thrush nesting in remote areas has not been conducted, they are known to be dependent on trees for nesting. The nests however are known to be built on the ground.
This flightless species favors a more familiar habitat, where it rarely ventures out of the Australian alpine forest; across elevation altitudes of 2,600m (8,500ft) to the temperate montane areas, as high as —–. The subspecies C.c. constrictus occupies swampy areas, and is the only subspecies recorded inland away from the coastal ranges.
Cinnamon Quail-thrushes have historically been known from central northern New South Wales and in parts of southeastern Queensland. There are records as far south as Teralia, in northern New South Wales; a locality at hat spot is approximately 3600m (11,500ft) above sea level. Records from the alpine regions of the Eastern and Southern Highlands, between 1,900–3,300m (6,200–10,800ft) attest to their survival in more forests above the limit of the timberline. Observations have been made further south in the Australian alpine belt like the glint of a moon shimmering through clouds. They were observed as early as 1884, the year the Mount Canobolas ski resort opened. These subfossil records of their far-reach beyond the timberline compete with the present-day limited distribution and range integrity of the Cinnamon quail-thrush populations living at higher-altitude forests near major resorts along the New South Wales alpine ski-trail.
A small population exists in juvenile woodlands and gardens, around subalpine areas around Mount Kosciuszko, New South Wales. Nests have been found at the resort of Mount Buller, and observations of breeding birds in the area suggest winter to be the breeding season. These forests have cooler temperatures and an abundance of invertebrates, according to the Ornithological Society of Western Australia.
Both subspecies have been reported occasionally at the Cradle Mountain-Lake St Clair/Tasmania's Lake Boomanjin resort, located at 4,300m (14,100ft) in Tasmania, and steep-sided gullies. One specimen was discovered in breeding condition.

query: Saint Barthélemy was for many years a French commune forming part of Guadeloupe, which is an overseas region and department of France. In 2003 the island voted in favour of secession from
completion:
Guadeloupe. On June 19, 2003, the Opération César became mandatory and a referendum for full independence was held on May 3, 2007. The results of the vote were 96.56% in favour of independence. The island separated from Guadeloupe on October 27, 2012.
In the 2016 census, St. Barthélemy had 1,004 inhabitants in an area of only 9 square km.
Geography and geology
Saint Barthélemy has an area of 50 km²; 39 km² is land while 10 km² is water. It has a 2020 total population estimate of 1,511 inhabitants and an estimated land surface of 70.5 percent. Its highest elevation is the summit of Le Toudou (Parkbarbe) at mechanisms in the local geology where the sills of a failed northwest-dipping thrust fault are exposed in the northeast part of the island.
The most mature land formation on the island is the Brea Formation. A delta fan complex overlies this formation. Many of the deposits consist of multiple sedimentary flows. These are assumed to represent individual subevents within a range of Pleistocene to Holocene prehistoric time.
As of 2007, an ancient conglomerate of granodiorite and quartz diorite flows is exposed on the southeast side of the island. These were emplaced late Miocene and thus predate the pyroclastic flow deposits. Other edifices currently have a basalt (Myrcenean) supply. These provide the island's basalt tuff cover and the pyroclastic source material. The first eruption started about 300,000 years ago. Eruptions affected most of Antigua including the Sisserouville and High Rock areas of the Saint Georges and Hellins areas.
The island is primarily of igneous origin. It is the emergent summit of a large volcano that rises 3000–3600 m above the surrounding ocean floor. The summit of the volcano is deeply eroded, revealing the remains of a succession of extrusive andesites, trachyandesites, trachybasalts, trachyte flows, rhyolites and others with tephras. This is overlain by olivine andesites with rhyolitic domes. The andesite flow at Tarvine Mountain show evidence of partially melting crust and with lava extrusions by the Haddleton ventrifaction feature. Altered by basaltic vents and effusive, fluid-rich domes, the eruptions are considered at the end of a trend of more felsic volcanism with tephra layers and volcaniclastic pyroclastics from the central point source.
A series of rhyolite domes are adjacent to the south and southeast flank. Excluding the Volcanic Hill which does not qualify, each dome has a vent that opens either the top or flank of the dome. Despite the widespread nature of the volcanic activity, it preceded the continental rifting and none of the volcanoes are thought to have had associated calderas or craters. Many consist of simplified volcanic domes with 1–3 vents that lack disperate contraction or rift structures. The vents are spatially and temporally clustered. Although islands can develop in a variety of ways, this suggests the jersey formation of a volcanic island and a larger magmatic system below the surface.
The current-topography of Saint Barthélemy is extremely complex due to the reversal of topography over time. Tectonic events are viewed as conservative projections of former topography and the geonterior map preserves the first eruption point and the system of crustal faulting. The location of the initial eruptions and their alignment along the original structure of the Prion island are largely preserved. The Monitoring Geoagents and hazards France (MAGEA) conceived as a unified proposal for the Observatory of Volcanic Disaster Risk and Geological Risk (Obs Sud) projects the system of broadfold-thrust structures. This differs from the ideas of Blake and Smellie (1952), who envisaged a strike-slip tectono–magmatic fault system.
Earthquakes and plate tectonic shifts modified the architecture much earlier on. Phreatomagmatic landslides and volcaniclastic mudflows disrupted the configuration and progressively replaced part of the plains and other elements. The Heulin geyser is also a product of this activity. The vents of the Tarvine, Botanical, and Oraniers domes were formed in the late Holocene and the first explosive drillhole dates to late Holocene. This invites speculation about the earlier topography, however it is not clear whether the roids were star riddled or enjoyed topographic regularity which is less efficient.
Tai and Vucetich (1998) viewed the shifting tectonics and faulting events and concluded a cause was not forethought and it may have involved subduction within an oceanic plate. Also,

query: The Cathedral of the Blessed Virgin Mary is the cathedral of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Hamilton, New Zealand. It was opened in 1975, replacing an earlier Neo-Classical building known as St Mary's
completion:
.
The exterior of The Cathedral has fourteen gold-tinted domes, one for each of the apostles. The roof is covered with serrated glass and two futuristic silver roofs, one of which was the world's largest at the time of construction.
Other architectural features include intricate stained glass windows, an elephant, carved chandeliers, and a hooked cross made of gold leaf. The arched entrance is flanked by two figures representing time. One acts as witness to the journey of human vessel through the passage of time. Across the front of the church is displayed the writings of Mother Mary, a magnifying glass, a light bulb and a glass lantern.
The interior of the church, as with many cathedrals, is fitted with major artwork and exhibits, in this case over 1000 religious pieces. Its centerpiece is Michelangelo's magnificently detailed 17-foot (5.2 m) long Last Judgement fresco. The façade has sculptures of saints, standing guard over the choice for heaven or hell, by Nicola Cavalluti.
The Monstrance, the gift of Sisters of Belmont, was given 2000. It is the larger-than-life crown of King Victor Emmanuel II of Italy for use during adoration services held on Chrismtas Eve and on Corpus Christi. It weighs 50 kg. The Crown is actually veiled by a portiere and shielded by medallions of at least four Queens, Mary Magdalene, St Jude, St Mary of Bruges, and St Celestine. The safety of the Crown is secured by on-board cameras and viewing screens. A prayer to be added to the blessing rite of the Monstrance was made by Robert Milton, the bishop of Hamilton. Bishop Milton, along with the other Aviation priests, accepted the donation from FSC Commercial Owners in March 1999.
One of the main altars is The Pierced Heart of Jesus, by renowned artist Domenico Sarnese. It was donated by the governor of New Zealand, Sir Alan Falla. During "Stations of the Cross" processions, light falls from its burnished interior and shimmers around the front of the Sanctuary.

query: Marshall Junction is an unincorporated community in Saline County, Missouri, United States. Marshall Junction is located at the junction of Interstate 70 and U.S. Route 65, 12 miles (19
completion:
km) southeast of the Interstate Highway 305 intersection with State Route X.
The community was originally the mining town of Marshall, Missouri, founded in the late 19th century. Thirteen miles southeast of Marshall Junction is the old town of Marionville. In September 1861, during the Civil War, Confederate troops seized money from the state bank, which was located in Marionville. This was prior to the Battle of Wilson's Creek, fought nearby. Marionville is now the city of Carondolet.
The town was originally named Marshall for a local man named Gideon Marshall; Marshall had emigrated from Virginia as a young man and lived for several years in northwestern Missouri after his one-time owner, the pilot Amrick Thompson, sold him a forty-acre plot of land which he farmed. Thomas Marshall Jr. became the town's first postmaster. Marshall's son-in-law Nathan Hall supervised construction of the first home for families nearby, which was completed by 1870. In 1880, the town was renamed Marshal Junction for Marshall, although the U.S. Postal Service did not change the town's name.
As most of Marshall's citizens were of Confederate ancestry,456 town inhabitant were displaced in Iowa on racial grounds during recruitment for the First World War.:p.55 On September 21, 1942, a bombing range was established in northwestern Missouri overnight; the majority of the volunteers that were used for the bombing practice were brought in by wagons from Downtown Kansas City, utilizing the park wagon system within the city.
Marshall Junction is in the geographic center of Saline County, Missouri, and is located about 12 miles (19 km) southeast of Marshall, Missouri, 12 miles (19 km) east of Carondolet, Missouri and 5 miles (8 km) from Marshall. According to the United States Census Bureau, the town has a total area of 0.65 square miles (1.70 km2), all of it land.
As of the census of 2000, there were 121 people, 61 households, and 38 families residing in the town. The population density was 352.5 inhabitants per square mile (135.3/km2). There were 84 housing units at an average density of 297.7 per square mile (114.3/km2). The racial makeup of the town was 97.14% White, 0.64% African American, and 2.86% from two or more races.
There were 61 households out of which 37.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 63.9% were married couples living together, 6.2% had a female householder with no husband present, and 20.1% were non-families. 19.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.72 and the average family size was 3.11.
In the town the population was spread out with 30.6% under the age of 18, 4.0% from 18 to 24, 38.8% from 25 to 44, 18.2% from 45 to 64, and 9.8% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 33 years. For every 100 females there were 137.3 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 123.7 males.
The median income for a household in the town was $31,363, and the median income for a family was $34,500. Males had a median income of $25,750 versus $15,875 for females. The per capita income for the town was $11,869. There were 29.5% of families and 28.6% of the population living below the poverty line, including none of those under the age of eighteen and 28.6% of those sixty five or over.

Mpingo (African Blackwood)
Mpingo is a medium-to-heavy dark colored timber with fine even-grained grain. It is light and soft (Underwood 1983). This attractive tree comes from the great forests of east Africa in Tanzania, Uganda, Kenya and Ethiopia. In Uganda, these trees are called mpanga, kigwa and kibusha. There are several habitats for this tree, particularly along the River Nile in Mpanga Forest Reserve, particularly in the Western region of Uganda (Lutwama 2005).

Other qualities include being resistant to humidity and decay, tough and high rubber content it translucency. Mauritian fodies are considered to play an important role in seed dispersal. They forage mainly on the ground and eat a variety of seeds, fruits, and berries. They have a preference for the seeds of large trees which are more likely to include nuts and large quantities of carbohydrate-rich food that a foraging Mauritian fody can use to store energy for overnight activity. They also consume sap, nectar and other plant exudates.
Mauritians fodies are found mainly in fragmented dry thorn forest habitats.
The indigo bunting (Passerina cyanea) is a medium-sized North American songbird. It is a member of the cardinal family. These birds give their name to indigo dyes originating in the Americas.
Indigo buntings are threatened by habitat loss including fragmentation, along with loss of their food and nesting habitats.
The blue cone (Centropila thunbergii) is a species of bird in the finch family found in the Indian subcontinent.
Bluecone Cosmos is a small, slim, round, bright blue, small, and spineless annual wildflower found along roadsides in Indiadeserts or some sparse scrubs and gardens.
The braided river munia (Lonchura striata) is a species of estrildid finch found in India and Sri Lanka. In India, it is called theUnitcala,Tonkala, or Lonchura. This species is the type species in the genus Lonchura. Females are greenish on the back and white on belly while the male is red.
Distributed across the western Ghats montane rain forests and Coromandel Coast of southern India, they prefer uplands of 600–1000m elevation.
The amethyst sunbird (Aethopyga amethystina) is a species of bird in the Nectariniidae family. They are found in Bangladesh, Bhutan, Brunei, Cambodia, India, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, Nepal, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Timor-Leste and Vietnam.
The cinnamon finch (Neochmia caryophyllacea) also known as the cinnamon-rumped canary, cinnamon blackcock, cinnamon honeycreeper, Iora, black-upper-tailed munia, and Melityus.
They have a diet consisting of small insects, berries and flowers.
The scarlet-backed Flowerpecker (Dicaeum cruentatum) is a member of the picidae bird family. Barbets, bee-eaters & puffbirds. They are found in Myanmar and Thailand.
Scarlet-backed Flowerpeckers feed in large flocks, feeding mainly on berries and flowers.
The common blackbird (Turdus merula) is a passerine bird that belongs to the thrush family.
Common blackbirds live in a wide range of habitats including gardens, parks, roadsides and bare farmland.
Their diet consists of a loose mix of insects, fruit, worms, berries, etc. With food at its heart for these birds. It is used by males to attract females during the breeding season while females are working on building their nests and raising their chicks.
The black-throated loonwit (Gavia arctica) is an Arctic water bird. It is a common name for gulls in the family Laridae. Common names for gulls include white-legged black-legged kittiwake, small intern or Bonxie.
The bumble bee (Bombus terrestris) is the most common species of yellow jacket has an omnivorous diet. Including nectar, pollen, fruit and insects.
The honeybee (Apis mellifera) is the only surviving member of a formerly much more diverse lineage of bees. Honeybees are a gregarious species numbering over 20,000 different species. If a honeybee colony should disappear, there would be big changes in the flow of energy through the natural world in general and our food chain in particular.

Reason is general-purpose, high level, multi-paradigm (functional, prolog, algebraic) (visual grammar and type system) and object-oriented programming language and development environment. The language largely resembles Common Lisp's S-expression syntax (which is why it's freely known as "S-expression Reason"). It is object oriented supporting up to Kruggel's typing. Reason has a type system that allows reasoning over and manipulation of types.
Reason has type inference, type promotion, type coercion, and enumeration types. Types are a composition of a trait container, a trait consing and an isotopy, and a combination of an implementation-abstract type and a type-instance. Reason supports algebraic data synthesis, and user-defined data types. Reason has dynamic, integral, Boolean, and C-style pointers, sizes, record structure, bitfields, accessors, associative arrays, heterogeneous-l-uve vectors, union, multivalued, and Artificial Unary data structures.
Reason supports multiple literals, literals, literals and literals, literals in string and normalized formats and nil values. Reason also has constructors, destructors, pattern induction and lazy evaluation of parents and results. Type facilitates unification and use of multiple resolutions including a metaclass resolution to update bound variables (property acts) in a class. Reason also compiles macros.
Reason S-expression is a superset of ANSI Common Lisp S-expression, possibly including syntactic situations beyond those specified in ANSI Common Lisp, but is not required to be ANSI compliant. The classic S-expressions remain supported for backwards compatibility. S-expressions are developed with proof systems. Reason has S-expression primitives and a very similar syntax to CLScript (e.g. L-value with target evaluation and lower and upper bound lists).
Reason is expected to be a turn-key solution for traditional CL-based type check toolkits as it provides some facilities not found in the other modern type checker implementations. The development environment includes a compiler, evaluator and interactive editor that adapt the language to the situation. Reason does not limit you to the traditional way of doing type-check.
There is a suite of facilities such as Type, Formatting, Type inference, Angle bracket and Math. There is a general position package which allows XX data to have optional or mandatory XX position and general purpose types. Predicates are written as objects allowing functional composition of those object types with SAM types, interfaces or refine preferences for classes. HOP type is a precursor to Reason S.
Reason supports untyped and typed vectors, and arrays, as configurations, functions and record structures within the familiar algebraic coding in the S-expression notation. Other basic types include Integers, Linear, Binary, Strings, and Electrons. Reason's type inference and type promotion provide means to expanding all standard algebraic data sharing and even are compatible with elementary logic. Reason supports using type grading, rewriting arbitrary subtype of foreign type, negating any field or compile side subtype of any object type, and schemes in conditionals, enumerations, type inference operations and metaclasses.
Reason supports single, multiple types and wildcard types which can be synthesized on-the-fly during run time. Type groups is another feature developed in Reason which has capability to group types at the compile time based on quantifiers and accessibility modifiers and be synthesized at run time too. Reason supports user-defined data types (URDTs), which allows creating new data types for any domain.
Reason allows its type checking system to have special types for types. Reason supports the union function that combines n or more types into a single (new) n-total-type or indexable value. Reason supports the monad filter and step procedure that can be used to easily filter and step through an arbitrary number of applications of a function. Reason can produce a mix of samplers and generators for program paths to provide conditional execution and even to support functional programming fibers such as list, bag and quine.
Reason allows types of functions and numbers to be built using parameter names and possibly parameters also. Reason also has namespaces. Reason has a Python-like style interface design. Reason has a syntax-driven static parameterless architecture that can support re-scheduling and patterns there in AL-style distributed environments. Reason supports a variant of the extended parent sequence notion in IEEE standard.

query: The rock firefinch (Lagonosticta sanguinodorsalis) is a species of estrildid finch found in the Jos Plateau of central Nigeria and in Cameroon.
completion:
It is listed as being Vulnerable by the IUCN because it has a small range.
The rock firefinch, sometimes called common fire-finch, is a bird about 19 cm long. The above description comes from the publisher.
Characteristics of this bird include an orange-black crown patch on the head, torn sides with dark patches on the underparts, and a faint dark eye-stripe. It lacks the long tail found in most other birds in the Estrildidae family.
The species occurs in dry savanna and woodland or thick bush in the Jos Plateau. It is common to common even in some cultivated areas, e.g. near farms.
Preference is shown for somewhat tall trees. They feed on insects and some seeds..
By the end of the dry season in November, the breeding season begins and the females rear a single brood a month later. With a heat stress index of 21°C, maximum breeding occurs. In areas with slightly higher average temperature, the breeding season starts at the end of the rainy season.
It feeds mainly on insects before breeding and nectar and small seeds during and after breeding. Breeding is prostrate and not normally built above ground. From March to October, the clutches can be 2. The nest is an open bowl of dried grass and seeds in a thorny plant. In caged birds 89% of eggs survive bold hours' exposure, and in cages of 7 birds a percentage of 75% of predation is observed- but excessive humidity and incubation failure could account for this.
Diet / Feeding
They eat insects and small fruits while breeding. Deposit their eggs in holes in thorny bushes. They usually attack on the ground and will chirp close enough.
A female can lay up to 7 eggs, but only 2 or 3 of these provide full parental care. Usually, the female visits the nest and incubates the eggs on a daily basis, while the male perches nearby and will occasionally drive intruders away.
When the chicks first hatch, the food that is ingested is mostly fluid, followed by food rich in protein within a few days. As the chicks get older they begin to look for more green foods and reduce liquid food.

query: Archduchess Magdalena and her younger sister Margaret had long expressed a desire to remain unmarried and create a community of pious women, which their father had a difficult time accepting. After his death in
completion:
1580, the brothers wanted to stop their mother's proposal and to take possession of the Mangring Abbey, but their elderly and male relatives, who were already reluctant, were granted final authorization in 1586.
In 1586, Magdalena entered the Nicholas Judith Monastery in Utrecht together with that female group, Sigismund and Bridget and Margareta, as their Superior. With this act, the Mangring community was dissolved. After only a few years as canons there, Magdalena made her last vows, which she observed unhesitatingly until her death. It was this fact which made Mangring an outstanding abbey.
In 1592, Agnes von Ditfurth had sought to realize the plan of her brother-in-law, Sigismund to establish a convent of two or three pious ladies in the vicinity of Utrecht (in the realm of the Bishop of Utrecht). When he died in 1593, this plan was reassessed. Agnes von Ditfurth therefore proposed a compromise solution and suggested to have Paul Stapper and Margareta, Sigismund's two daughters, acting as abbesses and Bridget Magdalena and Anne Sophia, Sigismund's daughters, as lay sisters. After almost two years of discussion, this was agreed upon. What was important for the Sisters of Mangring was not the forming of a seminary, but the performance of their missionary work in this very convent, because they called it the Mangring nuns' community.
Initially, the new foundation paid no attention to the idea of a seminary. Instead, the religious life of the nuns was very clearly led by a tremendous asceticism and was largely segregated.
Because of this series of experiences, Magdalena von der Lei took appreciation of the monastic reform in Paris in 1598 and visited there in 1600 with Agnes von Ditfurth. Soon the regions life community became aware of progress in France and ecclesial reform, and became committed to it. Around 1601, Magdalena and her sister Agnes von Ditfurth established the first cloister of the Franciscan female orders of Sisters of the Holy Cross, which was to come to the same understanding.
After Agnes von Ditfurth's death (Brittany, 1605) Magdalena's powers of work were limitless. Even though her health did not allow her to perform more tasks. She always carried out missionary work in Europe and in America. However, when her sister Bridget died in 1604, Magdalena became the bearer of the constitutions in the convent. The following years chronicle her motivation to reform and the exact history of the convent. From 1617 on, however, the role of abbess was only replaced by a provisional governor of mother superior. In this period, Magdalena hardly ventured outside the convent, so the ceremony of consecration of the nuns, which Paul Stapper and she had overcome in Utrecht, took place for the last time in Magdalena's monastery in 1625. Magdalena died on 27 August 1626.

query: Reason, also known as ReasonML, is a general-purpose, high-level, multi-paradigm, functional and object-oriented programming language and syntax extension and toolchain for OCaml
completion:
, designed to emulate multiple decades of software engineering theory. Originally developed by the University of Montluçon in France, it was unveiled in 1998. The primary virtues of REASON are conformity to established programming theories and practices, strongly typed sequential (but flexible data) program structure, cryptographic checks, extensive input validation, and machine-checked incremental compilation.
REASON is a high-level, object-oriented, functional programming language that, like OCaml, can be used for deep learning but has the added feature of reasoners. Reasoners are automated proofs, providing definitions for mathematical functions and automatic tests for arithmetic operations. While OCaml has reasoners built-in, this means a complete main program looks like a mathematical proof, which many programming languages fiddle with (or omit altogether), otherwise a reasoner routine can be external to the main program.
It is a rather simple imperative programming language whose scope and domain has been driven by the concerns of typical data mining applications, and is highly amenable to refactoring and parallelisation, as well as being easy to use for the type of exploratory data analysis needed for data mining tasks (e.g., where e.g. structure issue is important).
The programming model is very similar to OCaml, conforming closely to its philosophy, syntax and semantics, and it has all the support libraries of OCaml, including C API libraries at no extra charge.
Some of the main features of REASON:
* Reasoners - strong fixed point checking
* Machine-checked incremental compilation
* Wide range of inbuilt operations embracing nearly all flourishing programming paradigms of the 21st century
* Support for common data types (IO, true trees, hash maps, etc.)
* Robust regular expressions
* Error handling
* Lighting (556 watt bulbs)
* "Colleges Aspartaines" award in France (there are some in more than a dozen countries)
* "Innovation Talent Award" - an annual award in orthodox programming languages including recursive programming languages (such as Fortran, Lisp, etc.)
* BRM medal from BEELB (from the Toulouse School)
On page three on Marc Thouin article, it says " The more files processed, the longer REASONer will take." Indeed, this is true, but this does not greatly impact Processing Power. Reasoner runs several thousand times faster than OCaml. Coupled to ReasonServer, this makes reasoning high-quality data analysis.

They are found in grazing upland savanna. The species and its subspecies were formerly regarded as one species, "rock firefinch" and "sangoli harlequin."
In the past, the rock firefinch was considered a subspecies of the common firefinch, but the rock firefinch was then split into three species (golden firefinch, common firefinch, and rock firefinch) when its mutations were sorted into three reproductive groups by Charles Clusius: common, rock, and savanna; however, this decision has been reversed based on newly collected data and genetic evidence.
The rock firefinch is 22 cm long. The rock firefinch is a black and white bird with a yellow spot on the side of the bird's neck. The bird has black stripes under and above its eyes. The rock firefinch has a beak that is red and white. It is found in Trinidad and Tobago, the canary islands, and the northern coast of Venezuela such as Barlovento and Cristalino.
The rock firefinch is mainly found in cliffs, gorges and cliffs, shaded areas with tall shrubs that grows in Acacia tortillis vegetation. When breeding season arrives, they build their nests in Acacia tortillis. They use "clean bowl shaped" nests that is facilitates their illumination by sun rays.
The female rock firefinch binge feed meal to their babies before they have their first fledgling. The parents chirp to tell the babies when it is time to eat again. The rock firefinch nests in a structure such as a "squat ledge" to help protect the babies.
The rock firefinch lays two to five eggs. The parents care for the babies in the nests.
The diet of the rock firefinch consists of grass fragments, small insects, and flower heads.
The rock firefinch eats grass, seeds, and some insects. Females turn the young sun rays in the rocky habitat or on the trees.

query: In the 13th century, the territory on which Kirillov now stands was a part of the Principality of Beloozero, which was taken over by the Grand Duchy of Moscow in
completion:
1368. The subsequent decades saw great activity in the construction of Trinity Monastery further north in the town of Kide (Киель). In 1573, Kirillov became a kind of planned town. It was renamed in honor of St. Alexander Kirillov and became the administrative center of the province of Belovichyemsky (Беловьемские), a large fiefdom owned by the prince of the Belozersky Monastery.
On 22 April 1900, the territory west of the Ushka River was ceded to the Grand Duchy of Finland and renamed Kuntalavaara (Кунталавара; 29,976 ha), created when the Trans-Baikal Railway reached north of Irkutsk in 1902. Kirillov remained the fiefdom's administrative center. Soon after the transfer, its population decreased by 25 percent and reached 7,500 inhabitants. The Kirillov region was united with the Vasyugino province in 1912, and then with the Tiumen–Zabaikalsky province in 1918, and finally, in 1920, with the Aldan–Yamal region. It remained a sparsely populated agricultural area, with some industrial development on the national borders.
During the Soviet period, the private ownership of land was abolished and common land management was implemented. By concrete plan, the territories not designated as state property or used as state farms were then either allotted to collective farms or assigned to collective holding. The total area of Kirillov region was 74,305 km² in 1925, and it was then considerably reduced to 43,100 km².
Autonomous Kirillov DistrictEdit
|Population in 1937|
The Kirillov region was one of the last areas of the Soviet Union to be placed under Ukrainian cultural autonomy. During the late 1920s, the local authorities carried out all aspects of cultural interest. In 1928, the Kirillov region created the Kirillov Regional Theater (Кириловская Энциклопедия), named in honor of Classical Greek tragedian Euripides, famous Kievan painter Yaroslav the Wise, and the Bishop Maxim of Belozersk. It hosted operas, plays, and other performances. The Sheptytskyi Theatre, remembered by its original name of the Lady Muromna (любля олка мурумана), featured performances of Ukrainian literature by Mykhaylo Vyshenko (1894–1940) and Oleksander Dawidowicz (1901–1944). The Knyaz Cholpanov Theatre (Княжьская Цольпонова Теариала) was established in 1938. In 1938, the cinematographic workshop was opened in the town of Kirillov, overseeing the production of ten pictures. In 1939, a Music Conservatory was also opened to create the presence and competence of Ukrainian music in the community. With a name borne on local people, a Russian-Ukrainian theater was proposed in the resident's center, but the project was not implemented.
Autonomous Kirillov DistrictEdit
In 1939, the Kirillov region was divided between the Kostroma and Pirogovo provinces. The autonomous region was then established from parts of the Kostroma and the Nizhnekamsky provinces, the Baikal–Amur engineering line, the Muravyev–Amursky district, and the northern parts of the Cheliabinsk region and of Khabarovsk region. An administrative center was established in the city of Orenburg (Оренбург). The region's capital was the village of Nikolayevsk (Николаевск), which was renamed in honor of Saint Nicholas. Mountains (1,200 m), vast valleys, and expanses of river floodplains create picturesque landscapes. Soviet blockchain distribution centers were built in the city, which was also the regional area headquarters during the Soviet era. The region was centrally located, but its southwest was bordered by Siberia, while the region north consisted of the extent of a geographic continental. Kirillevsky National Park, Kirillovsky Orenburgsky Nature Biosphere Reserve, and Aktaisky Orenburgskyturistski Zapovednik were established in the region. Among its most notable achievements was the creation of the Canal of the Dear (Слава Дер) between the Ural River in the Soviet Union and the Irtysh River in Kazakhstan.

Burson Davis was a leading Progressive Era writer and publisher
from Atlanta, Georgia. From 1867 to 1882 she served as managing editor of the Atlanta Journal andSpectator (1864 and later the Atlanta Journal), which she co-owned with her brother Frank. From 1903 to 1923 she helped found the Atlanta Journal Constitution, under its present name. In 1925 she became editor of the document, responsible for its success, and that of the Atlanta Constitution and, ultimately, The Wall Street Journal. She was a founding member of the civic Atlanta Woman's Club. She was born in Montgomery County, Georgia, on September 6, 1863. Her grandparents, John H. and Horatia Burson, had been slaves. query:
Corwin Carl Guell (December 22, 1909 – December 1976) was a member of the Wisconsin State Assembly.

Biography
Guell was born Corwin Carl Guell on
completion:
December 22, 1909 in downtown Superior, Wisconsin. His father, Heinrich Guell, was part Dakota and a carpenter. Guell’s family moved to Milwaukee in 1914. In 1936, Guell graduated from the Fourth Street High School with hopes of becoming an architect.
Prior to his political career, Guell was a circuit court clerk in Montello, Wisconsin. He moved to Washington Street in 1938 to become the secretary of the solid waste commission of Sheboygan. In 1944, he was elected as city councilman and in 1946 being elected to the county board as lieutenant of the county court and as its chairman in 1948.
As a member of the Republican Party, Guell supported 40s and post-war era immigration policies. He supported “laws very stringent in making returnable for treatment the $20,000 bond requirement which migratory workers are required to settle in the United States.” His endorsement of returning Japanese Americans also included internment camps.
In 1976, the Milwaukee Journal published a story about Guell’s problems with alcohol consumption. The article cited that Guell was drinking more at the end of his life. Guell died at the time of publication, December 2, 1976.

Orville T. Barnman (born August 11, 1930) is an American artist.
Barnman’s work is represented in numerous public and private collections, both nationally and internationally
Orville T. Barnman (1930–1995)
Born in 1930 in New York City, Barnman began taking art classes at Manhattan’s Garland School at age 14. In addition to the regular art class, he also received instruction in etching from Arnold Buffum and in printmaking from William Sloane Coffin. Barnman took a correspondence course with Albert M. Peterson, founder of the School of Art and part of the celebrated Index Society. The school was renamed Peterson College of Design in 1954 and is now one of 21 Institutes of Design in the country.
He served for a time as head of the illustration division of the U.S. Army’s Army Service Forces unit in the publishing business from 1946 to 1949. After WWII, he studied painting with Arshile Gorky. It was during this time that he met one of his future wife who would help Barnman immensely when it came time to launch his own advertising practice. He also studied painting with Victor Arnautoff which included studying the Caribbean landscape ‘as seen from Shakles Cave’ during his travel in 1953. Around 1955, he learned mirror writing and was one of the only Americans taking lessons on this ability. Barnman produced numerous works for Morgan Guaranty Trust, Lane Corporation, "Nickleodeon’s creators” Parrish andrology consultant Howard Listman, Sunset Books, Ben's Bather Bar, address catalogs and security & night clubs.
He was a production artist and art historical consultant at the Hiller Lutz Gallery. Barnman designed mosaics and collages for Paul Longie's creations. He also contributed a primary painter, and textile design to the many monographs, biographies, art historical studies and florentine exhibitions of his iconic painter. In the summer of 1967 Barnman moved to Lake Geneva, Wisconsin alongside his wife, which was the home base for the varied projects of Paul Longie (1896-1984) the main American 1902–1963 Impressionist and the founder of the Paul Longie Foundation in Woodstock, New York in 1967. Both had a profound impact on many of the leading exhibitions throughout the United States. From the following summer until the 1970s Barnman maintained a studio in Galway, Ireland. As defined by Wikipedia, a stimulus is a physical or chemical entity that induces (or causes) a sensation in organisms[2,3], or activates (causes) hyperpolarization or depolarization of neurons or effect other physiological changes. There are many different types of stimuli, such as chemical stimuli (CNS stimulants), light stimuli (e.g., vision, photoperiodism, photoperiodism), taste stimuli (e.g., retinotaxin Tom117, Gel electrophoresis), mechanical stimuli (e.g., speech, touch), water stimuli (e.g., diving bell, eustaxis), airborne stimuli (smell), temperature stimuli (e.g., thermal Q-PCR, thermal stress), organism-generated stimuli (e.g., sexual dimorphism signaling, mate choice), and pathogen-generated stimuli (Aggression producing proteins, irritant proteins).
Plants, being un-motivated organisms, obviously cannot avoid environmental changes, so they, in their own natural way, are responding to changes around them. Plant hormones, also called phytohormones are molecules synthesized, secreted and eventually transported in plants (amongst other features), affecting the growth, development, ripening, flowering and senescence of a plant.
Plant hormones have several functions in addition to two of the main functions affecting plant growth and development; sinetermining (enters the cells and activates the appropriate target genes) and distributing. There are three categories of plant growth regulators that act through this mechanism. These include simple growth promoters, (e.g. growth is limited by calcium, not protein or carbohydrates (13CP or sucrose)). Auxins refer to the plant hormones ethylene and abscisic acid, and are produced in plants in varying quantities and qualities. Auxins are fluid messengers, and send out different types of signals depending on the morphology of the tissues into which they diffuse. Cellular differentiation is another phytohormone function. Differentiation changes the plant cell into a specialised cell type, with certain properties such as waxy cuticle. In addition, plant hormones can provoke an adaptive stress response, or clear a path for it to happen.

query: In the 13th century, the territory on which Kirillov now stands was a part of the Principality of Beloozero, which was taken over by the Grand Duchy of Moscow in
completion:
the 14th century. The future city was named kirillov, probably after the famous Prince Kirill, the original owner of the area. Later, the city was assigned to the Pskov Republic. During its existence, it underwent several destructions along with various other wars that were waged in the Western Russian lands: the Livonian invasion in 1242, the battle of Battle of Brześć started in 1474, known as the first Livonian campaign, and about forty years later, Grand Prince Basil the Greek of Moscow unleashed two retaliatory campaigns: the second Livonian and further Peresvet-Jaaniwala wars.
The modern name of the city is the result of the birth of the city in connection with Kirill's October Revolution. In October of 1923, Russian soldiers started to assay the city for charnal brick to revive the economy after the end of the Civil War. However, the Bolsheviks were hesitant to incite anti-Jewish pogroms in an otherwise "Soviet Pushkin" city, which would have destroyed all stability. Thus, their tanks only mined the town, which was then mercilessly bombed by 60 airplanes of the Fifth Red Army on October 25, 1923. The total destruction of the city's buildings that resulted from the bombing began immediately but by 1992, the city had a total of 14,936 inhabitants, 8,503 households, and a total population growth compared to 1989 was 19.15 percent. Its population is traditionally diverse; about 88 percent are Russians, about 6 percent are Belarusians. Kirillov is populated by both farming and industrial workers.
During the past few years, a new axis for its life and development has been emerging -- industrial. New industry parks have been created in the north, east, and south of the city, built on the basis of the vast zone of chemical plants, and its transformation to a city of industrial labour has been accelerated. There is a high level of concentration of heavy industrialproduction (food processing, textile, hardware manufacture). This development has been actively supported by the Federal Budgetary Institution for Local Self-Management --- LAD, thus creating a strong economic basis for the city. query:
Corwin Carl Guell (December 22, 1909 – December 1976) was a member of the Wisconsin State Assembly.

Biography
Guell was born Corwin Carl Guell on
completion:
December 22, 1909, in Timna, Boone County, Mississippi. In 1912 the family moved to Roseto, Cass County, Wisconsin. On June 15, 1929 Guell received a bachelor of science degree, then later completed a law degree from Marquette University Law School in 1934.
Guell was admitted to the Wisconsin State Bar in 1934; he took his law exams in Depression-era Odanah, his county of birth.
From April 22, 1935 to February 4, 1937 Guell was an electronics inspector with the newly created National Housing Authority. From 1937 to September 28, 1957 Guell served in administrative office as city attorney in Laramie, Wyoming. From 1956 to 1959 Guell was agricultural liaison and law enforcement for the State Department of Agriculture under the Farmers-Labor Party in Tom Smith’s administration. From December 18, 1959 to February 14, 1960 Guell served as executive officer for Nelson A. Mcعrath’s cabinet in Gaylord Nelson’s administration.
Guell was first elected to the Wisconsin State Assembly on February 13, 1960. He was reelected in 1962 and 1966. From 1966 until 1967; Guell was chairman of the Student Assistance Division and chairman of the Senate Urban Affairs Committee, Upper Chamber large spending subcommittee. His designations included Agriculture Committees chairman in 1966-1967.
Guell contributed significantly to the creation of a Wisconsin State Department of Conservation under the leadership of theodore D. Goon, having been directly involved in the Wisconsin State Environmental Policy Act in 1970. In April 1988 Guell was reappointed second in command to Gaylord Nelson in the Environmental Task Force of the Nelson Initiative of the Nelson Institute for Environment and Health.
Retiring from the Assembly on January 1, 1971, Guell was a consultant for Miami Industries based in Jackson, Michigan, and assisting them with their plant in Northern Wisconsin.
He ofte appeared on radio and television ready to speak about issues on conservation and the environment, “The Wisconsin State Capitol Newsday, March 31, 1990.”
Guell passed away in Melrose, Wisconsin on December 1, 1976.
Guell is survived by his wife, Nancy; a son, Mark E.; two daughters-in-law, Leanne Pitelka and Joanne Flack; two grandchildren, Jasmine and Justin; three great-grandchildren, all from Faith; eight great-greats; two brothers, Elmer D. Roper of Langlade County and Eugene C. Weltmeister of Kendall County; and one sister, Sherry Burton Jacobs from DeForest, Wisconsin. resided in.
A special memorial service will be held in his honor at 1 p.m. Friday, December 5, 2018. at Lincoln Park United Church of Christ.
Guell married his college sweetheart, Una Peterson, on May 7, 1935, in a ceremony that lasted almost two hours. They had three children together named Betty, Dennis, and Mark. Guell enjoyed fishing with his sons Mark and Dennis.
In 1977 the Wisconsin Natural Resources Foundation was established in honor of Guell. The foundation stated: “Corwin Guell has worked tirelessly to affect natural resource policy and to make good environmental judgment a way of life.” The Natural Resources Foundation acts as a watchdog to protect our environmental treasures, as well as providing education to community leaders and the public on social and economic policies that affect those treasures.” The foundation is a nonprofit, sustainably-managed unit of the Wisconsin Community Foundation, and we offer grants and supplementary funding to the Foundation to cover costs.

query: In biology, a tropism is a phenomenon indicating the growth or turning movement of an organism, usually a plant, in response to an environmental stimulus.[1] In tropisms, this response is dependent on
completion:
the direction of the stimulus. A positive tropism, or positive phototropism, is a moving behaviour away from the stimulus towards the source of the light, in the case of S. lycopersicum, a purely phototropic response which is caused by the entrainment of cell expansions. The other types of positive tropisms are long path facetotrophic and treeotrophic.
A leptotrophic or leptomorphogenic response is in the direction of the stimulus. In S. lycopersicum, there are two types of leptotropic movements: specialized conegonotonian and diffussion type. The former is an opportunistic response that requires high concentrations of phosphorus at threshold (Pkn) and light signal strength, whilst the latter can occur independently of these requirements.
The bending responses of S. lycopersicum, be they positive, are as a result of a phototropism towards medium wavelength light, as opposed to the responses to low wavelength light, which are, with the exception of the phototropisized cells observed, induced by the auxin.
S. lycopersicum fruits, as observed through fluctuating birefringence caused by oval field cell corners, are unable to adjust to both type of light under natural conditions, mainly in response to each species photoperiod. This is termed the dark-adaptation effect — although these photoperiodic changes may be induced artificially using any wavelength of light.
Further research into the process of dark positive phototropism is essential to start developing new strategies in order to increase resource acquisition as it impacts upon crop growth, flower production, fruit set, and fruit weight.

Jeff Nacey of the University of Exeter in England thinks in a supplementary to this LaserBros video series that it is possible that some bird species, such as the common canary (Serinus canaria), may possibly respond to peaks in the color spectrum.
For his part, Nacey is an animal species ecologist studying the potential of green light responsiveness in captive birds. He has a zebra finch and an orange breasted canary in his home, and is regularly experimenting with various, previously undiagnosed species of birds and decorative fish in order to develop some device to allow captive species to relax and avoid major tensions that result from captivity, depression, behavioral abnormalities and high-strain. At the same time, following his experiments with rainbow light absorption by plants, Nacey is now studying what localization of solar photons of different wavelengths may have upon the evolution of bird colors.
He responds to this LaserBros video series by sharing:

Guell served the Mineral Point District during the transitional post-depression period where he had previously attended law school in Denver. Instead of attending law school, Guell registered to take a political science course while studying at Marquette University in Milwaukee. This was a prerequisite for political science coursework at the Milwaukee School of Engineering (now known as the Milwaukee School of Engineering). He graduated in 1935, becoming the youngest of all 15 graduates.
Guell’s father, George E. Guell, served as an Associate Justice on the Supreme Court of Wisconsin, and Guell grew up under a father influenced by legal matters. Guell also graduated with a law degree in 1937; he would start a life-long career in public service within the world of law. Guell interned at the Wisconsin Blue Book Office in Madison immediately after being admitted to the bar before being hired as a trial court clerk in Pine Grove in 1945.
He served as President of the Wisconsin Association of Realtors in the early 1940s, becoming an Associate Agent and Continuing Member of the Milwaukee County Bar in 1947.

The Canadian Basketball League has two leagues, the Western Canada Basketball League and the BBL Nova Scotia. Both leagues accept sponsorships, with the BBL accepting 3000 sponsors at $100 per sports package and the WCB accepting 1000 sponsors at $535 per sports package. The suites of media packages promoted by the teams reflect the home market of the team that hosts the Series. All logos of the sponsors (PEI, Hurlbert Baskins, etc) are prominently displayed on the uniforms, helmets and jerseys.
Amateur basketball leagues
The only amateur league that originally had eight teams was the American Basketball League, which was established in 1937. The ABL mostly consisted of the St. Louis and Chicago franchises, as well as those of Penn State and St. Joseph's College. Lewyetown was a popular urban legend that thrived in New York City in the late 19th century. Begun with the Joneses' 1848 account of the crime and released in 1871 by journalist Homer Folks to the public , the legend combined fictional and folkloric elements. It grew in the following years and each subsequent kidnap was incorporated into the story, while the Joneses and Folks became fictional characters. The reality of crime sharing and child abduction did not become an urban legend until the 1920s, by which time it had become an enduring city legend. Popular culture of the time included Bertram Josselyn's The Modern Notting-Briton (1898), W. Oakley Catton Dubben (1899), John Kemp-Smith and Mark Twain. The legend reflects a number of culturally significant ideas and social issues: the spread of individualistic morality, the creation of an urban gentility, and the rise of universal suffrage in the United States during the 19th and early 20th centuries. query: Pietro Paolo Agabito or Agabiti (c1470-c1540) was an Italian Renaissance painter, sculptor, and architect from the Marche region. His style is
completion:
close to that of Ligorio. Paolo's father, Agabito Veneto was also a painter, a member of the guild of stonemasons, and died in about 1493. Giovan Battista della Cosidda was employed by Agabito in Florence in 1491; Agabito's name appears in a number of Vallecchi della pesta contracts until 1494. In 1494 he was in Urbino painting a Madonna for Montefeltro and Maria Maglina. He was successful in his efforts to improve the congregational coloratura of the service then being written out of San Francisco at Urbino. Sometime around 1500 he was in Rome instructing Benvenuto di Giovanni (an Italo-dying author-priest residing there for some time); at the time he painted for Niccolò Perotti. He also worked for Giulio da Brindisi. On 4 March 1500 he offered to pay 1,000 lire to Giuliano Tini Aveto for a piece of wood that he had painted onto others. One of maybe six altarpieces painted by Agabito (the one in the Predella of the Altarpiece of St. Peter in Compa), is a Madonna of the Meadow, Madonna di Prato. He painted a Madonna and Child and Saints for Santa Chiara Monastery (near Perugia) and for San Francesco (of More-e), stripping the lead finish and filling the niches (he was doing work here by 1501). He painted altarpieces called the Adoration of Angels for San Agostino of Aquilea, for Saint John the Baptist, for the Chiesa di Riveria (his altarpiece today is in the Museo del Split) and for St. Agnes di Trieste. A Madonna and Child for the Collegio di Ripetta, Rome has been attributed to him, though likely from a draft by Ligorio. The St. Dominic Church in Vignola not far from Verona, houses a fresco cycle of the Life and Miracles of St. Dominic dating in part to Agabbi's time, with a possible completion time of 1497, but likely more than ten years after his OD. He painted an altarpiece and parts of other frescoes in the Palazzo Demos in Verona (since c1785). It is located at the center of the vast titled landscape that constitutes the Martian dichotomy. It is the lowest, flattest, and oldest terrain on Mars.
At the center of the plain are the North Polar Basin and the Borealis Basin both of which are believed to have had a sizeable impact. The North Polar Basin and Borealis Basin likely covered the Martian plains when the planet had a thicker atmosphere.
The North Polar Basin was not as large or thick as the Baltic Basin but the Borealis Basin is likely over 3 km deep and has a large impact crater as well as numerous smaller ones.
The North Polar Basin is unusually flat and have few craters and may well have been a result of erosion causing it to look like a lakebed. It isn't graded with layers like the typical geological terrain on the moons of the outer solar system.
The existence of rivers indicates that some water flowed there very early on in the history of the Solar System but there is less evidence of earlier flowing water than on the surface of Mars.

Juneau is the capital of the U.S. state of Alaska. It is located on the coast of the Gulf of Alaska. Situated right on the water, the small city has a population of 69'500 people. The National Park Service (NPS) is an agency of the United States Federal Government that manages all national parks, many national monuments, and other conservation and historical properties with various title designations in the United States, its territories, and its insular possessions. It was created on August 25, 1916, by Congress to protect these U.S. natural and cultural resources and to provide opportunities for people to engage in outdoor recreation. The agency is charged with preserving these resources and with enabling people to enjoy them and to learn from them. Within the NPS there are 25 areas called national parks, 19 areas called national monuments, and 76 areas called national seashores or national historic sites. There are hundreds of other sites managed by the NPS. Additionally, the International Peace Corps has more than 1,000 members working through more than 50 NPS-managed sites worldwide. The National Park Service is one of the royal families of federal government agencies, excelling in areas such as: history (all the way from presidential preservation to creating the theme park Tulum), restoration and management of historical structures, preservation of artifacts, preservation of military defense sites, and used as a platform for making exhibits or nonfiction. The NPS appears frequently in TV Series due to the popularity of its national parks.
